es d’Orléans and Authorial Intentions in the Middle English Ballade 84 -- tPart IV WORDS, MUSIC, SPEECH -- t15 All Adam’s Children: The Early Middle English Lyric Sequence in Oxford, Jesus College, MS 29 (II) -- t16 Musical and Poetical Form in Stond wel, moder, under rode -- t17 Tutivillus and the Policing of Speech in Oxford, Bodleian Library, MS Douce 104 -- t18 Have This in Mind: Word and Image in Audelay’s Writing -- t19 ‘The Dance of the Intellect among Words’: Wyatt’s In eternum and Late Medieval Lyric Practice -- tAfterword: The Study of Medieval Lyrics in 1960s Oxford and Today -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Manuscripts -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA collection attesting to the richness and lasting appeal of these short forms of Middle English verse.The body of short Middle English poems conventionally known as lyrics is characterized by wonderful variety. Taking many different forms, and covering an enormous number of subjects, these poems have proved at once attractive andchallenging for modern readers and scholars. This collection of essays explores a range of Middle English lyrics from the thirteenth to the early sixteenth century, both religious and secular in flavour. It directs attention to the intrinsic qualities of these short poems and at the same time explores their capacity to illuminate important aspects of medieval cultural practice and production: forms of piety, contemporary conditions and events, the historyof feelings and emotions, and the relationships of image, song, performance and speech to the written word. The issues covered in the essays include editing lyrics; lyric manuscripts; affect; visuality; mouvance and transformation; and the relationships between words, music and speech. A particularly distinctive feature of the collection is that most of the essays take as a point of departure a specific lyric whose particularities are explored within wider-ranging critical argument. JULIA BOFFEY is Professor of Medieval Studies in the Department of English at Queen Mary University of London; CHRISTIANIA WHITEHEAD is Professor of Middle English Literature at the University of Warwick. Contributors: Anne Baden-Daintree, Julia Boffey, Anne Marie D'Arcy, Thomas G. Duncan, Susanna Fein, Mary C. Flannery, Jane Griffiths, Joel Grossman, John C. Hirsh, Hetta Elizabeth Howes, Natalie Jones, Michael P. Kuczynski, A.S. Lazikani, Daniel McCann, Denis Renevey, Elizabeth Robertson, Annie Sutherland, Mary Wellesley, Christiania Whitehead, Katherine Zieman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish poetry-Middle English, 1100-1500-History and criticism. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aLyric.  aclose reading.  apoem.  averse.1 aBaden-Daintree, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoffey, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoffey, Julia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aD'Arcy, Anne Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Thomas G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Arcy, Anne Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFein, Susanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlannery, Mary C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffiths, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrossman, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsch, John C, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsh, John C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l